menu "SPI NAND Flash configuration"

    config NAND_FLASH_VERIFY_WRITE
        bool "Verify SPI NAND flash writes"
        default n
        help
            If this option is enabled, any time SPI NAND flash is written then the data will be read
            back and verified. This can catch hardware problems with SPI NAND flash, or flash which
            was not erased before verification.

    config NAND_PAGE_REGISTER_CACHE
        bool "Page-register cache – skip redundant READ PAGE on repeated access"
        default n
        help
            The NAND chip holds one page in its internal register.  When this
            option is enabled, the driver remembers which page is currently
            loaded and skips the redundant READ PAGE command (~25–100 µs)
            on back-to-back reads of the same page.  The tracking is reset
            automatically after every program or erase.

            Disable to force a fresh READ PAGE on every read — useful for
            measuring baseline read latency without this optimisation.

    config NAND_FLASH_ENABLE_BDL
        bool "Enable Block Device Layer (BDL) support"
        depends on IDF_INIT_VERSION >= "6.0"
        default n
        help
            Enables a layered block-device architecture (ESP-IDF >= 6.0 only).
            This exposes the NAND flash through the standard block-device
            interface, with separate layers for raw flash access and
            wear-levelled logical sectors.

            When enabled, use spi_nand_flash_init_with_layers() to initialise
            the device.  The legacy spi_nand_flash_init_device() API is no
            longer available and will return an error.

    config DHARA_META_CACHE_SLOTS
        int "Dhara metadata cache – DRAM slots for NAND metadata pages"
        range 0 8
        default 0
        help
            Number of full NAND pages kept in DRAM to avoid re-reading
            metadata that the wear-leveling layer accesses repeatedly.
            Each slot costs one page of RAM (typically 2048 bytes).

            Set to 0 to disable (no extra RAM usage).  Values of 2–4 are a
            reasonable starting point on targets with spare DRAM.

    config DHARA_MAP_PATH_CACHE
        bool "Dhara map-path cache – cache sector lookup for sequential access"
        default n
        help
            When enabled, consecutive reads to sequentially-numbered sectors
            skip the parts of the internal lookup tree that have already been
            traversed.  This can eliminate most of the per-sector metadata
            reads during sequential workloads.

            Costs 136 bytes of static RAM.  Disable for purely random
            access patterns where the overhead offers no benefit.

    config NAND_ENABLE_STATS
        bool "Collect runtime statistics (Linux host tests only)"
        depends on IDF_TARGET_LINUX
        default n
        help
            Track per-operation counters (erase/program/read counts, cache
            hit rates, wear distribution) during host-test runs.  The stats
            are exposed through the spi_nand_flash_get_cache_stats() API and
            are used by the host test and evaluation apps.

            Linux target only — has no effect on firmware builds.

    config NAND_FLASH_PROG_PAGE_RELIEF
        bool "Program page relief – skip pages with high ECC corrections before programming"
        default n
        help
            Before programming a page, the NAND chip reads it back to check
            its condition.  If the ECC engine reports a correctable-bit count
            at or above the chosen threshold, that page is skipped and the
            next available page is used instead — the block is not marked bad.

            This prevents programming pages that are already showing wear
            signs, reducing the risk of future uncorrectable errors.
            Uncorrectable ECC still fails the operation immediately.

    choice NAND_FLASH_PROG_PAGE_RELIEF_THRESHOLD
        prompt "ECC correction threshold for page relief"
        depends on NAND_FLASH_PROG_PAGE_RELIEF
        default NAND_RELIEF_AT_4_TO_6_BITS

        config NAND_RELIEF_AT_1_TO_3_BITS
            bool "1–3 bits corrected (aggressive)"
        config NAND_RELIEF_AT_4_TO_6_BITS
            bool "4–6 bits corrected (balanced)"
        config NAND_RELIEF_AT_7_TO_8_BITS
            bool "7–8 bits corrected (conservative)"
    endchoice

    config NAND_FLASH_FAULT_SIM
        bool "Enable NAND fault-injection simulator (for linux target ftl_eval app)"
        depends on IDF_TARGET_LINUX
        default n
        help
            When enabled, nand_fault_sim.c replaces nand_impl_linux.c at link time.
            The fault simulator implements the same nand_impl interface and supports
            configurable fault injection: factory bad blocks, erase/program wear-out,
            retention failure, per-operation probabilistic failures, power-loss crash
            with torn writes, and ECC read-disturb simulation.
            Linux target only. Zero impact on firmware builds.
            Used by the ftl_eval evaluation app.

endmenu
